Cell["\<\
We see that unless the window thickness is matched to the frequencies of the \
radiation we use, the window can reflect up to ~35% of incident power. \
However, when the frequency is matched, ideally no power is reflected at all. \
Even if we change the frequency by ~1.6 GHz from each minimum, the \
reflectivity will stay below ~5%.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7294407475112977`*^9, 3.7294408398914385`*^9}, {
  3.7294409679880247`*^9, 3.729440968964551*^9}, {3.7294410222467823`*^9, 
  3.7294410857314053`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"37dd8082-6634-4336-944e-\
17d0a529eb88"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Half-wave windows", "Subsubsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7294406513505464`*^9, 3.729440658339717*^9}, 
   3.8951705742069187`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"2a84630c-5b69-418f-af25-\
1b23b674d121"],

Cell["\<\
Due to the periodicity of the reflection coefficient, we only need a single \
window thicknesses to cover our four frequencies (13.3797 GHz, 26.7595 GHz, \
40.1392 GHz, 53.519 GHz), namely, in millimeters,\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.729438801211228*^9, 3.72943886152567*^9}, {
  3.7294389502309794`*^9, 3.7294389523734646`*^9}, {3.7294390350946965`*^9, 
  3.7294390401170855`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"e52d2787-7dd2-4c9a-9f36-\
d84d1213b3d1"],

